2. Create the API Route (app/api/get-participant-token/route.ts)\par
This API endpoint will be called by your frontend when a user wants to join a room. It checks if the user is verified, then creates a signed token.\par
\par
TypeScript\par
import \{ AccessToken \} from 'livekit-server-sdk';\par
import \{ NextRequest, NextResponse \} from 'next/server';\par
\par
export async function POST(req: NextRequest) \{\par
  const body = await req.json();\par
  const \{ room, username, isBroadcaster \} = body;\par
\par
  // 1. Validate environment variables\par
  const apiKey = process.env.LIVEKIT_API_KEY;\par
  const apiSecret = process.env.LIVEKIT_API_SECRET;\par
\par
  if (!apiKey || !apiSecret) \{\par
    return NextResponse.json(\{ error: "Server misconfigured" \}, \{ status: 500 \});\par
  \}\par
\par
  // 2. Create the Access Token\par
  const at = new AccessToken(apiKey, apiSecret, \{ identity: username \});\par
\par
  // 3. Add Permissions\par
  at.addGrant(\{\par
    roomJoin: true,\par
    room: room,\par
    canPublish: isBroadcaster, // Only the broadcaster can publish video\par
    canSubscribe: true,\par
  \});\par
\par
  const token = await at.toJwt();\par
\par
  return NextResponse.json(\{ token \});\par
\}\par
3. Conceptual Workflow of a Broadcast\par
The token exchange follows this secure sequence:\par
\par
Request: Your frontend sends a request to the API with the user's ID and the room name.\par
\par
Verify: The API verifies the user's isVerifiedAdult status in your Postgres database.\par
\par
Sign: The server generates a JWT (JSON Web Token) signed with your API_SECRET.\par
\par
Connect: The client sends this token to the LiveKit Server. The server checks the signature; if valid, it opens the WebSocket connection for the video stream.\par
\par
